Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] This experiment determined that there are various factors involved in genetics and development that have the ability to affect the complex metabolic mechanisms in organisms. These organic reactions often entail multiple enzymes and ligands, and altering one enzyme or ligand in one step of these processes has the ability to alter all following mechanisms and reactions. This showed not only the complexity of metabolic reactions but also their delicacy and how easily a mutation in enzymes can alter the function and net outcome of the reaction.
explainConcepts[SQ002] This explained that one gene is responsible for the production of one specific enzyme depending on the sequence of codons that the transcribed mRNA codes for during translation and the resulting peptide. This hypothesis explained how a gene codes for one enzyme and one enzyme only, but it did not take into consideration overlapping genes.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Sickle cell anemia is the result of a mutation in a single nucleotide of the gene that codes for hemoglobin. Altering this one nucleotide in the form of a mutation demonstrated that the one-gene-one-enzyme hypothesis is not quite correct because the hemoglobin is composed of multiple proteins, but a mutation in only one results in sickle cell anemia. This showed an exception to the one gene one enzyme hypothesis because a mutation in one gene affected the function of a tertiary, multiprotein complex.
phenomenonA Archibald Gerard first suggested that genes controlled 'inborn errors of metabolism' in 1923.
phenomenonA[comment] A mutation in the enzyme involved in the second step of tryptophan metabolism has the potential to alter the organic mechanism and halt the metabolism of tryptophan entirely due to the mutated enzyme resulting in a substrate that does not bind to the enzyme involved in the third step of tryptophan metabolism.
phenomenonB The genetic basis of sickle cell anemia demonstrates that the one-gene-one enzyme hypothesis is not quite correct.
phenomenonB[comment] A mutation in the enzyme involved in the first step of glycerol metabolism has the potential to alter the organic mechanism and halt the metabolism of glycerol entirely due to the mutated enzyme resulting in a substrate that does not bind to the enzyme involved in the second step of glycerol metabolism.

explainConcepts[SQ001] Archibald Gerard discovered inborn errors of metabolism. Gerard’s research proposed an explanation for epistasis. For example,he found that alkaptonuria, a disease that makes urine black because of the presence of gentesate. His results showed that the disease was prevalent in those whose parents were closely related.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The one gene-one enzyme hypothesis proposes that genes are regulated by the production of enzymes where every gene is responsible for making one enzyme that affects one step during the metabolic pathway. This founded the science of biochemical genetics.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The genetic basis of sickle cell anemia demonstrates that the one-gene-one enzyme hypothesis is not quite correct because sickle cell anemia is caused my many mutations that are affected by many enzymes. Many enzymes affect can influence one gene or one enzyme can affect many genes.

groupTime460 98.16

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Archibald Gerard suggested the idea that inborn errors of metabolism can occur due to the control of genes; since particular genes code for certain types of enzymes, problems can arise when toxic or abnormal substances are accumulated within an organism that inhibit his or her ability to function. The specific type of problem that Gerard suggested derives from a group of genetic diseases that cause metabolism disorders, leading to an organism's inability to synthesize compounds, develop normally, or carry a normal life.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Based on the idea that genes code for enzymes and errors can occur within metabolic pathways, George Beadle was able to discover the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis, stating that each gene produces strictly one single enzyme within these metabolic pathways. Beadle utilized Neurospora and other model organisms to illustrate this hypothesis, saying that one gene is capable of ultimately controlling one metabolic pathway.
explainConcepts[SQ003] There are certain processes that have demonstrated the invalidity of the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis, including the genetic basis of sickle cell anemia. Sickle cell anemia occurs when a genetic mutation affects the hemoglobin of an organism, leading to distorted red blood cells. This process demonstrates the invalidity of the hypothesis because multiple genes can control the same metabolic pathway within the organism.
phenomenonA George Beadle proposed the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis.
phenomenonA[comment] Now, we know that not all genes control the direct construction of enzymes because certain genes can code for structural proteins or polypeptides, often leading to multiple genes coding for the same molecules.
phenomenonB Archibald Gerard first suggested that genes controlled 'inborn errors of metabolism' in 1923.
phenomenonB[comment] Many individuals that experience inborn errors of metabolism can live their entire lives with deafness, blindness, abnormal pigmentation, low blood pressure, depression, and many other diseases.

Additionally, I understand that the problems within errors of metabolism occur due to accumulation of various toxic substances, often leading to abnormal function or the inability to synthesize compounds. Lastly, I understand that this was determined based on a study of the organism alkaptonuria.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that this hypothesis was developed based on Gerard's suggestion of the inborn errors of metabolism, stating that each gene ultimately codes for one metabolic pathway. In other words, each gene is responsible for generating a single enzyme that leads to the effects of a single metabolic pathway. Furthermore, I understand that this process led to a large portion of the development of molecular biology and biochemical genetics. Lastly, I understand that this process is not fully accurate in many cases.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis was believed to be correct for quite sometime; however, processes such a sickle cell anemia illustrate that certain genes may code for polypeptides and other molecules. Also, I understand that, within these molecules, more than one gene can be held responsible for the same metabolic pathway, rejecting the hypothesis that one gene must code directly for a single enzyme.

explainConcepts[SQ002] This discovery was certainly one of the more important in genetics. It was a huge leap forward, increasing our understanding of how DNA information translates to a protein product that the cell can utilize. Later experimentation revealed that Beadle's conclusion was not entirely accurate. It was, however, a step in the right direction. We now know that one protein codes for one polypeptide.
explainConcepts[SQ003] This evolved the conclusion that Beadle had come to. By altering single proteins in a metabolic pathways, researchers concluded that instead one gene seemed to code for one polypeptide.

explainConcepts[SQ001] Archibald Garrod discovered inborn errors of metabolism. An explanation for epistasis is an important manifestation of Garrod’s research, albeit indirectly. When Garrod studied alkaptonuria, a disorder that makes urine quickly turn black due to the presence of gentesate, he noticed that it was prevalent among populations whose parents were closely related
explainConcepts[SQ002] The one gene-one enzyme hypothesis is the idea that genes act through the production of enzymes, with each gene responsible for producing a single enzyme that in turn affects a single step in a metabolic pathway. The concept was proposed by George Beadle
explainConcepts[SQ003] The one gene-one enzyme hypothesis is the idea that genes act through the production of enzymes, with each gene responsible for producing a single enzyme that in turn affects a single step in a metabolic pathway.
phenomenonA Archibald Gerard first suggested that genes controlled 'inborn errors of metabolism' in 1923.
phenomenonA[comment] Inborn errors of metabolism are rare genetic disorders in which the body cannot properly turn food into energy. The disorders are usually caused by defects in specific proteins that help break down parts of food.
phenomenonB George Beadle proposed the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis.
phenomenonB[comment] "one gene-one polypeptide" hypothesis is now considered too simple to describe the relationship between genes and proteins
groupTime461 445.81

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Inborn errors of metabolism form a large class of genetic diseases involving congenital disorders of metabolism. The majority are due to defects of single genes that code for enzymes that facilitate conversion of various substances (substrates) into others (products). In most of the disorders, problems arise due to accumulation of substances which are toxic or interfere with normal function, or to the effects of reduced ability to synthesize essential compounds. Inborn errors of metabolism are now often referred to as congenital metabolic diseases or inherited metabolic diseases.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] The one gene-one enzyme hypothesis is the idea that genes act through the production of enzymes, with each gene responsible for producing a single enzyme that in turn affects a single step in a metabolic pathway. The concept was proposed by George Beadle
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] The one gene-one enzyme hypothesis is the idea that genes act through the production of enzymes, with each gene responsible for producing a single enzyme that in turn affects a single step in a metabolic pathway.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Inborn errors of metabolism form a large class of genetic diseases involving congenital disorders of metabolism. The majority are due to defects of single genes that code for enzymes that facilitate conversion of various substances (substrates) into others (products). In most of the disorders, problems arise due to accumulation of substances which are toxic or interfere with normal function, or to the effects of reduced ability to synthesize essential compounds. Inborn errors of metabolism are now often referred to as congenital metabolic diseases or inherited metabolic diseases.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The one gene–one enzyme hypothesis, proposed by George Wells Beadle in the US in 1941, is the theory that each gene directly produces a single enzyme, which consequently affects an individual step in a metabolic pathway.

groupTime460 205.41

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Garrod studied human disorders that could be inherited. He studied albinism, cystinuria, and alkaptonuria. He looked for patterns of inheritance of alkaptonuria and eventually concluded that it was genetic in nature. Garrod concluded the inherited condition was the result of an alternative mode of metabolism, thus implying that hereditary information was controlling chemical reactions in the body. Thus, this suggests that there are errors in the metabolism caused by changes in the genes.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Beadle investigated nutritional mutations in the pink bread mold Neurospora crassa. They studied how different mutant strains of the mold would be affected when grown in a medium that was incomplete. If no growth of a culture in a minimal medium occurred then it was inferred that the strain was mutant and not able to produce the nutrient that is missing in the medium. It seemed likely to Beadle that each nutritional mutation caused the loss of the enzymatic activity that facilitates an essential reaction in wild-type organisms. It also appeared that a mutation could be found for nearly any enzymatically controlled reaction, thus suggesting that one gene specifies one enzyme.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The first direct evidence that genes specify proteins other than enzymes came from the work on mutant hemoglobin molecules derived from humans with sickle-cell anemia. These individuals have erythrocytes that are not shaped like a normal erythrocyte. These erythrocytes are proteins whose genotype and phenotype can be traced back to a single pair of alleles. Thus, if these alleles control the production and viability of the erythrocytes then it can be deducted that genes code for proteins other than just enzymes.
phenomenonA The genetic basis of sickle cell anemia demonstrates that the one-gene-one enzyme hypothesis is not quite correct.
phenomenonA[comment] Sickle-cell anemia is a disease that affects roughly 5% of the population. Since it has been determined that genes are responsible for all proteins then geneticists can discover the unique gene sequence responsible for sickle cell anemia and the possibility of an individual expressing the disease.
phenomenonB Archibald Gerard first suggested that genes controlled 'inborn errors of metabolism' in 1923.
phenomenonB[comment] Without the "inborn errors of metabolism," or mutations, that Gerrod discovered, geneticists would not have an explanation for how many diseases caused by mutations arise. For instance, sickle-cell anemia could not be traced to a mutation in the hemoglobin gene if it was not known that genes can cause such a mutation.

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that Garrod studied albinism, cystinuria and alkaptonuria because he was interested in human disorders that seemed to be inherited. I understand that his studies of alkaptonuria produced some good evidence. Individuals with this disorder have a disruption in an important metabolic pathway, and I understand that Garrod was interested in how this disruption arises. I understand that he concluded that this disease was in fact genetic in nature and that it was due to an alternative mode of metabolism. I also understand that this implies that hereditary information controls chemical reactions in the body, which would suggest that a change in genes would cause a change in the metabolism of a cell.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that Beadle studied a pink bread mold. I understand that Beadle and Tatum induced mutations in cultures of the mold and then observed whether or not the cultures grew in a minimal medium. By determining whether or not cultures with mutations grew in a medium lacking a specific nutrient, the scientists could determine whether or not the culture could produce the missing nutrient on their own. If the cells in a specific minimal medium do not grow, then this means that the enzyme that would process the missing nutrient is not present. Thus,I understand that the one gene: one enzyme hypothesis came from this research since it showed that the genes of a cell directly affect the enzyme production of the cell and that mutations could change this enzyme activity.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that sickle-cell anemia is a disease in which erythrocytes in affected individuals are abnormally shaped. I understand that affected individuals have erythrocytes that are elongated and curved. I understand that James Neel and E. A. Beet demonstrated that the disease exhibits Mendelian inheritance. I understand that through pedigree analysis the scientists determined three phenotypes for a single pair of alleles responsible for the erythrocytes. I understand that since these alleles were isolated as responsible for the erythrocyte production, it can be concluded that the erythrocytes are coded by genes. Since erythrocytes are not enzymes but are proteins, the one gene: one protein hypothesis serves as more correct than the one gene: one enzyme hypothesis.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that mutations are random in an organism's genes. I understand that mutations do not arise from need but rather are spontaneous. Then, through natural selection those mutations that are favorable for the organism will be passed on to offspring. I understand that through this, mutations could be thought to serve an organism's "needs". However, since the mutations arise spontaneously, they are not based off needs. I understand that natural selection may favor certain mutations after they arise, but the needs do not produce the mutation.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Archibald Gerard discovered that there are many errors in the human genome that often cause disease. He called them inborn errors of metabolism because the error occurs in a single gene, that codes for particular enzymes, which often play a key role in a cell's metabolic pathways.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Beadle proposed that one gene codes for one single, particular enzyme, which then has important and very particular function in metabolic pathways. He proposed this because he demonstrated that one gene in a fruit fly controlled a single, specific chemical reaction in the fruit fly, which one enzyme controlled
explainConcepts[SQ003] Instead of the one-gene-one enzyme hypothesis, it seems more likely that is a one-gene-one polypeptide hypothesis. This is because some enzymes are composed of different polypeptides, which come from different genes. One gene is very unlikely to code for one single enzyme by itself. It often takes multiple genes to make an enzyme.
phenomenonA The genetic basis of sickle cell anemia demonstrates that the one-gene-one enzyme hypothesis is not quite correct.
phenomenonA[comment] Sickle Cell shows us that there can be many genes that can code for just one enzyme. Different genes create different polypeptides, which come together to make an enzyme This is shown when different polypeptides come in and to make hemoglobin work. If one polypeptide is not made properly, it will not let the enzyme function to its full capacity and therefore the blood cell will not function properly, hence the sickling of the cell.
phenomenonB George Beadle proposed the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis.
phenomenonB[comment] George Beadle used the fruit fly to come up with this hypothesis and the one enzyme he found just happened to have been made by just one gene, but it is often that multiple genes make one enzyme. They all come together to make a single enzyme for metabolic function.

explainConcepts[SQ001] Inborn errors of metabolism involves the use of enzymes in metabolism. When these enzymes are not functional, then it blocks the pathway, which prevents metabolism of some important substances that can cause disease. For example, the phenylketonuria block prevents the production of tyrosine, which causes this process to undergo a different pathway that can lead to nerve damage and mental retardation.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The one gene-one enzyme hypothesis was important because it as the first theory that suggested one non-functional gene could result in an enzymatic block in metabolism. This hypothesis was proposed by studying different mutations in Neurospora, which is a good organism to use for studying since it is haploid.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The one-gene-one-enzyme hypothesis became the one-gene-one-polypeptide hypothesis by studying sickle cell anemia in hemoglobin. For example, the sickle cell trait occurs by a mutation on the beta chain of a protein in the sixth amino acid preventing the protein from cross-linking. This study shows that only one polypeptide in this quaternary structure protein is mutated and causes this missfolding.

phenomenonB The genetic basis of sickle cell anemia demonstrates that the one-gene-one enzyme hypothesis is not quite correct.
phenomenonB[comment] I find this study interesting because it uses the quaternary structure of a hemoglobin molecule to decide that one gene codes for one polypeptide instead of one enzyme. Hemoglobin can become mutation in one primary structure polypeptide to create a disease like sickle cell anemia.

groupTime460 51.51

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Archibald Garrod studied alkaptonuria by looking at patterns of inheritance. He found that consanguineous parents, that were unaffected themselves, had a much higher chance of producing offspring with this rare but serious disease. Because of the differences in incidence rates between related and not related parents, Garrod concluded that because this condition was inherited, it must be a result of an alternative mode of metabolism controlled by hereditary information. He labeled what we now know to be genes are “unit factors” and what we now know as enzymes he called “ferments.” Garrod’s work, like many other brilliant scientists before him, was far ahead of his time, and he was only recognized for the importance of his work almost 30 years later.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Through his research done in 1933, George Beadle was the first to support the idea that genes are responsible for making enzymes in the body through evidence in his research. After beginning his experiments with mutant genes in fruit flies, he collaborated with Edward Tatum in investigation Neurospora crassa. After using X-rays to increase the mutation rate in Neurospora crassa, they used a series of minimal plating techniques supplemented with various molecules and nutrients in the biochemical pathway of tyrosine. They concluded that each of the mutants lacked an enzyme in the pathway, and therefore, when the induced mutations affected one gene that was responsible for one enzyme, the culture could not grow unless supplemented by the end product of the missing enzyme in the pathway.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Experiments with human hemoglobin and sickle cell anemia provided that the one-gene-one enzyme hypothesis was incorrect because it was too limiting. Different individuals express different specific phenotypic traits even when they have mutations on the same gene. The two factors that modified the one-gene: one-enzyme hypothesis were (1) while nearly all enzymes are proteins, not all proteins are enzymes, and (2) proteins often have a subunit structure consisting of two or more polypeptides. Through these experiments, the one gene: one-polypeptide chain hypothesis was established, as mutants seemed to affect only one polypeptide, which could then go on to form multi-subunit proteins.
phenomenonA George Beadle proposed the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis.
phenomenonA[comment] Even though this hypothesis was later disproved via a series of studies that favored a one gene-one protein hypothesis, foundational research and preliminary hypotheses are the starting point for many answers gained in research. The work of many researchers in various fields builds in different ways on one another to give the scientific community a holistic understanding of various topics.
phenomenonB The genetic basis of sickle cell anemia demonstrates that the one-gene-one enzyme hypothesis is not quite correct.
phenomenonB[comment] Sickle cell anemia is a disease that is of particular interest to me because of the insights it has provided to the scientific community. The ability of sickle cell anemia to be so deadly as well as confer a selective advantage in protection from malaria shows how truly delicate and balanced our bodies and their natural processes are in maintaining our health.
groupTime461 1101.25

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that the work done by Archibald Garrod was critical in establishing the basis for future research into the field of how genetic material that is inherited by offspring is relayed into functional enzymes and proteins in the cell. I understand that, like in most other discoveries, the future work done by scientists may not have been possible without his foundational work. Looking back, I understand that what Garrod termed “unit factors” were really genes, and what he termed “ferments” were really what we know today to be enzymes.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand the one-gene: one-enzyme hypothesis in that in Beadle’s study, they looked at the overall biochemical pathway involved in the synthesis of tyrosine. When an organism with a mutant was blocked at any step of the pathway (which they discovered through various cultures of minimal medium supplement with various molecules in the pathway), Beadle assumed that the mutation induced by the x-ray was affecting a specific gene that would have been responsible for the particular enzyme that catalyzed this pathway.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that sick cell anemia helped scientists establish the one gene: one polypeptide hypothesis because the mutation that causes sickle cell disease affects only one beta subunit in the four subunit polypeptide hemoglobin. Researchers discovered that because (1) most enzymes are proteins but not all proteins are enzymes and (2) proteins are often comprised of multiple subunits. These two factors led them to establish the one-gene: one-polypeptide hypothesis, as many proteins that do not function or cause disease, such as sickle cell anemia, are the result of just one nonfunctional polypeptide chain that serves as one of the four subunits in the entire molecule.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that mutations are random relative to the organisms “needs” in that the organism does not choose to mutate or have any direction in the mutations accumulated. Mutants arise and are passed on to progeny when the random mutation confers some sort of selective advantage to the organism, which allows it to produce more offspring than other organisms of its kind. Over time, these positive mutations result in more adaptively fit organisms, and the allele frequency of these mutated genes increases in populations over time.

phenomenonB[comment] Gerard's work applies to various diseases, such as albinism and Phenylketonuria (PKU). explainConcepts[SQ001] Gerard first gave the idea of Inborn errors of metabolism. He showed that they are rare genetic disorders in which the body cannot properly turn food into energy. explainConcepts[SQ002] George Beadle used Neurospora crass to prove one gene one enzyme hypothesis. He chose Neurospora crass because it spent most of its life in haploid state so they dont have to worry about second set of genes or dominant or recessive alleles. In the lab they allowed this Neurospora to grow in a minimal culture. In order for it to grow normally it should have all the genes so it has to be protrotrophic. They reasoned that if they mutate any one of the genes that makes an enzyme, for example gene for arganin, then they should get a Neurospora strain that cannot grow on minimal medium. The mutant would be able to grow if only they added the enzyme product as a supplement. There was 7 mutation they found which did not allow the conversion of citrulline to argenine. Based on this and x-ray method they concluded that one gene transcribes one enzyme.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The reason one gene one enzyme hypothesis was later changed to one gene one polypetide hypothesis is because of more complicated proteins like Haemoglobin. Haemoglobin have 4 polypeptides chain that come together and combine and make a functional protein that functions normally. Therefore, one gene one enzyme hypothesis was later modified when it was realised that genes also encoded nonenzyme protiens and polypeptide chains. It is now known that some genes code for various types of RNA involved in protien synthesis

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] One of the disorders that Gerard studied was alkaptonuria. He looked at the patterns of inheritance for this disease and found that it was genetic in nature. Of the many families he studied, the majority of the cases of alkaptonuria were confined to families. Families that had cases were sometimes found to have first cousins that were married, which is more likely to bring back recessive genes to offspring. This information led Gerard to conclude that the inherited condition was the result of a different mode of metabolism, which implied that hereditary information controls chemical reactions in the body.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Beadle and Tatum worked with Neurospora and induced different genetic mutations to produce strains that had genetic blocks of reactions essential to the growth of the organism. They isolated and studied hundreds of mutants and it seemed that each nutritional mutation caused the loss of the enzymatic activity that facilitates an essential reaction in the wild-type organism. This provided solid evidence that one gene specifies one enzymes.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Work began to arise that showed that not all genes coded for enzymes. Work with sickle-cell anemia showed that genes may specify proteins other than enzymes. People with sickle-cell anemia had mutant hemoglobin molecules. Pauling concluded that a chemical difference exists between normal and sickle-cell hemoglobin. Further research showed that a gene codes for a single polypeptide chain, showing that Beadle and Tatum were on the right path but not specific enough in their original hypothesis.
phenomenonA The genetic basis of sickle cell anemia demonstrates that the one-gene-one enzyme hypothesis is not quite correct.
phenomenonA[comment] People with sickle cell anemia have a gene that codes for hemoglobin that differs by only one amino acid in on part of the hemoglobin but this amino acid difference is still enough to cause a significant and somewhat problematic change in the overall protein structure. One gene that is mutated can have a very large effect in the protein that it codes for.
phenomenonB Archibald Gerard first suggested that genes controlled 'inborn errors of metabolism' in 1923.
phenomenonB[comment] Gerard studied the disease alkaptonuria. This disorder has a disruption in a metabolic pathway that makes it unable for a person suffering from it to metabolize homogentisic acid. He concluded that this disease was inherited genetically after studying many people, most of whom where related, with that disorder.
groupTime461 3385.9

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Gerard was interested in several disorders that seemed to be inherited. He looked at albinism, cystinuria and alkaptonuria. When studying alkaptonuria, he concluded that this disorder was genetic in nature. Of the 32 cases he had been studying, 19 of them had come from seven families. In some of the families where the children were affected, the parents were unaffected but were known to be first cousins. Gerard came to the conclusion that alkaptonuria was the result of an alternative mode of metabolism (a mutated enzyme), which implied that hereditary information controlled the chemical reactions in the body.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] George Beadle and Edward Tatum with Neurospora because a lot was already know about its biochemistry and mutations could be induced relatively easily. They worked to induce mutations to produce strains that had genetic blocks of reactions essential to the growth of the organism. Many mutated organisms were produced and each type of nutritional mutation was determined. Hundreds of mutants were isolated and studied to determine what the organism was deficient in and unable to produce. With their data, Beadle and Tatum found that it was likely that each nutritional mutation caused the loss of the enzymatic activity that facilitates an essential reaction in the wild type organism. This led them to believe that one gene specifies one enzyme. This is what Gerard had also proposed 30 years earlier, though in more exact terms.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] A study of sickle cell anemia was some of the first evidence that genes specify proteins other than enzymes. Linus Pauling found that hemoglobins that are isolated from diseased and normal people differed in their rates of electrophoretic migration. This lead him and his colleagues to believe that there was a chemical difference between normal and sickle cell hemoglobins. Using different techniques, it was found that the different hemoglobins differ by one amino acid change. This was important because hemoglobin is not an enzyme but just a protein. This meant that the “one gene: one enzyme” hypothesis was not entirely accurate anymore.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] When mutations occur, it is not because they are advantageous to the organism. All mutations are entirely random. Induced mutations may be the result of either natural or artificial agents. Spontaneous mutations occur relatively rarely in organisms. The rate of mutation may increase or decrease in an organism but mutations are still random. Mutations may occur and specific mutations may be selected for in a population if they are adaptive. The Luria-Delbruck fluctuation test was used to verify the idea that mutations arise spontaneously in the absence of selective pressure rather than being a consequence of selective pressure.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Archibald Gerard referred to inherited diseases as inborn errors of metabolism. These are a large class of congenital disorders of metabolism. Most are caused by defects of single genes that code for enzymes that catalyze reactions. Most of the disorders are due to toxic substances that interfere with normal function or reduce the ability to synthesize essential molecules. The term inborn error of metabolism was coined by a Archibald Garrod, a British physician.
explainConcepts[SQ002] This is the idea that genes produce enzymes, where each gene is responsible for producing a single enzyme. The concept was proposed by George Beadle and Edward Tatum in a 1941 paper on genetic mutations in mold, Neurospora crass. This finding is often considered the first significant result in molecular biology.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Red blood cells normally have protein (not an enzyme) hemoglobin A, which consists of two alpha and two beta chains. People with sickle cell anemia have a mutation in the beta chain, but there can be many different variations. This shows that the genes for hemoglobin do not code for one enzyme only. It was proven through protein fingerprinting that genetic variations in proteins like sickle cell hemoglobin could be limited to differences in a single polypeptide chain, which lead to a one gene-one polypeptide hypothesis instead
phenomenonA Archibald Gerard first suggested that genes controlled 'inborn errors of metabolism' in 1923.
phenomenonA[comment] This topic relates to inherited diseases in our world. There "inborn errors" are within the genes and are passes down from generation to generation. For example, one of my friends has ehlers danlos syndrome, which has been passed down in her family for generations.
phenomenonB George Beadle proposed the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis.
phenomenonB[comment] It would make sense for one gene to code for one enzyme; however, we now know that one gene codes for one polypeptide. because some proteins are not enzymes. For example, chymotrypsin is an enzyme and hemoglobin is just a protein.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Archibald Gerard used mendelian genetics and physical observation to suggest that genes control metabolism. He looked at a rare disease, alkaptonuria, that causes brown to black urine. He looked at families with the disease and concluded it was inherited recessively on an autosomal chromosome. So, it seemed that a gene was affecting the metabolism of the individuals.
explainConcepts[SQ002] George beadle used neurospora and e. coli to arrive at his hypothesis. He looked at the metabolic pathway of arginine. He saw that different mutants stopped at different points in the pathway. This suggested that a specific enzyme was missing as a result of the different mutations.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Sickle cell anemia is a disease of hemoglobin. Hemoglobin has a tertiary structure with 4 subunits, 2 alpha domains and 2 beta domains. A mutation in different genes can cause sick cell anemia. A healthy hemoglobin enzyme requires 4 separate polypeptides be produces correctly. So, multiple genes are required. So, it is more accurate to say one gene codes for one polypeptide.
phenomenonA The genetic basis of sickle cell anemia demonstrates that the one-gene-one enzyme hypothesis is not quite correct.
phenomenonA[comment] Different mutations can cause sickle cell anemia.
phenomenonB Archibald Gerard first suggested that genes controlled 'inborn errors of metabolism' in 1923.
phenomenonB[comment] Phenlyketonuria (PKU) is a genetic disease that interrupts the metabolism of phenylalanine.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] While studying the disease alkaptonuria, Garrod proposed that diseases are the result of genes not properly producing what is needed for the body's chemical pathways. This was the first proposal of a biochemical basis in genes.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The one gene-one enzyme hypothesis states that genes are responsible for the enzymatic activity in cells. Simply put, each gene has a sequence that encodes for one enzyme.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Studies of sickle cell showed that a mutation in a single polypeptide can change the function of the organism. What resulted was the one gene-one polypeptide hypothesis that states that each gene encodes for one polypeptide, which can function by itself or be paired in a multimeric compound.
phenomenonA The genetic basis of sickle cell anemia demonstrates that the one-gene-one enzyme hypothesis is not quite correct.
phenomenonA[comment] Studies of sickle cell showed that the causative mutation only changed one polypeptide chain in the hemoglobin protein. The protein is made of multiple polypeptides, so the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis is technically not correct. Instead, each polypeptide, whether functioning alone or with other polypeptides, is encoded by one gene.
phenomenonB Archibald Gerard first suggested that genes controlled 'inborn errors of metabolism' in 1923.
phenomenonB[comment] Although Garrod's hypothesis was not correct, it served a basis for future study. His biochemical proposal led to many other scientists, including Beadle, looking into the relationship between genes and chemistry. It was the rough beginning of molecular biology.

groupTime461 2286.8

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Garrod discovered inborn errors of metabolism. He noticed that it was prevalent among populations whose parents were closely related. Garrad followed an autosomal recessive pattern of inheritance and figured out that it was caused by a mutation in a gene encoding an enzyme involved in the metabolism of a class of compounds called alkapton.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] The one gene-one enzyme hypothesis is the idea that genes act through the production of enzymes. Each gene responsible for producing a single enzyme that affects a single step in a metabolic pathway. The results that showed proved against the one-enzyme hypothesis showed that different genes were responsible for different enzymatic reactions in the production of hormones that controlled the organism's reproduction
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Ingram showed through protein fingerprinting that genetic variations in proteins could have differences in polypeptide chain in a multimeric protein leading to the, one gene-one polypeptide. groupTime461 2497.02

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Gerard was studying the disorder alkaptonuria in which individuals have a disruption in an important metabolic pathway and cannot metabolize homogentisic acid. He determined that this disorder is much more common in 1st cousin marriages. This is because related members that have children together have a greater possibility of passing on homozygous traits like that of alkaptonuria. Normal individuals can metabolize HA but afflicted individuals cannot. He postulated that these people cannot metabolize homogentisic acid because they lack a certain enzyme to do so.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Beadle showed nutritional mutations in Neurospora caused loss of enzymatic activity. The synthesis of the amino acid arginine was investigated. Seven arginine auxotrophs mutant strains were studied. Mutations prevented conversion from citrulline to arginine. It also appeared that a mutation could be found for nearly any enzymatically controlled reaction. His experiment led to his hypothesis that one gene specifies one enzyme.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Normal and sickle-cell hemoglobin chemically differ by two molecules: HbA and HbS. This was found by using starch gel electrophoresis in which HbA migrated farther than HbS, suggesting that its net negative charge was greater. The fingerprinting technique demonstrated HbA and HbS hemoglobins differ by a single peptide fragment. Further analysis then revealed a single amino acid change: Valine was substituted for glutamic acid at the sixth position of beta chain.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Luria and Delbruck presented the first direct evidence that mutations do not occur as part of an adaptive mechanism, but instead take place spontaneously and randomly. The fluctuation test used T1 bacteriophage and E. coli cells. Mutations can occur in E. coli cells that make the cells resistant to T1. If mutations occur adaptively there would be constant probability of acquiring a mutation. This was not seen, although. Mutations were random and occurred spontaneously.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Archibald Gerard noticed that some inherited diseases resulted in harmful alterations in biochemistry and suggested that genes played a role in these alterations. He made this suggestion in his 1923 book Inborn Errors of Metabolism, which was the first suggestion of how genes worked.
explainConcepts[SQ002] George Beadle was the first to show that genes are directly responsible for the synthesis of enzymes. Beadle observed that some mutations would render the mold Neurospora incapable of growing in a minimal medium, but the same Neurospora colony could grow in a medium that provided a specific enzyme. This led him to form the one gene, one enzyme hypothesis.
explainConcepts[SQ003] We have learned from sickle cell anemia that hemoglobin is not formed by a single protein from a single gene. Instead, it is formed by an alpha chain and a beta chain, which are encoded by different genes. Sickle cell anemia occurs in people with a mutation on the gene that codes for the beta chain. This means that one gene makes one polypeptide, but not necessarily one enzyme.
phenomenonA George Beadle proposed the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis.
phenomenonA[comment] The one gene, one enzyme hypothesis makes a lot of sense, and to be honest, I didn't realize that it was false until this class.
phenomenonB The genetic basis of sickle cell anemia demonstrates that the one-gene-one enzyme hypothesis is not quite correct.
phenomenonB[comment] I find this phenomenon very interesting from an evolutionary point of view. It is almost like co-evolution within a genome--very fascinating that something like that can just happen out of purely random mutations, but not-so-random natural selection.
groupTime461 9362.09

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that Archibald Gerard noticed that some inherited diseases resulted in harmful alterations in biochemistry and suggested that genes played a role in these alterations. He made this suggestion in his 1923 book Inborn Errors of Metabolism, which was the first suggestion of how genes worked. Some examples of these "inborn errors" include diseases like Alkaptonuria, which results in homogentisic acid in the urine. I understand that Gerard reasoned that unaffected individuals could metabolize homogentisic acid, while affected individuals could not due to a missing enzyme. Another example is Phenylketonuria (PKU).
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that George Beadle was the first to show that genes are directly responsible for the synthesis of enzymes. Beadle observed that some mutations would render the mold Neurospora incapable of growing in a minimal medium, but the same Neurospora colony could grow in a medium that provided a specific enzyme. This led him to form the one gene, one enzyme hypothesis. He recognized that the mutations took the organism's ability to synthesize the necessary enzyme away, meaning that genes must be the framework with which organisms synthesize enzymes. Furthermore, because a single mutation only took the ability to synthesize one enzyme away, each gene must only be responsible for one enzyme.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that that hemoglobin is not formed by a single protein from a single gene. Instead, it is formed by an alpha chain and a beta chain, which are encoded by different genes. Sickle cell anemia occurs in people with a mutation on the gene that codes for the beta chain. This means that one gene makes one polypeptide, but not necessarily one enzyme.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that while natural selection and evolution are not random, mutations are random. They occur at the same rate at consistently arbitrary locations within the genome, regardless of the outside environment. Just because an organism or population may be in need of a new superpower, that doesn't mean that the DNA will suddenly begin mutating at an increased rate or in certain regions of the genome, in order to give the organism a new superpower.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Garrod formulated the hypothesis that hereditary information controls the chemical reactions in the body. He observed that the disorder alkaptonuria (a rare trait) was more likely to be expressed among consanguineous offspring. Knowing that recessive heterozygous traits have a higher chance of being expressed as a result of inbreeding, he concluded that there had to be a heritable trait passed on to individuals to code for enzymatic processes.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Beadle's test with Neurospora proved that mutating a gene results in altering the functionality of the organism. By isolating particular mutants with their complementary minimal media growth, he was able to determine that mutating a gene in an organism could render the organism unable to grow without having the supplement added to the medium. This proved that a single gene coded for the organism to synthesize a particular supplement.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Vernon Ingram proved, through the use of fingerprinting technique, that valine was substituted for glutamic acid at a particular position in the Beta chain of hemoglobin. This mutation is a recognized trait in sickle cell anemic patients, and this proved that a single mutation in the polypeptide chain of the Beta hemoglobin results from one gene alteration.
phenomenonA Archibald Gerard first suggested that genes controlled 'inborn errors of metabolism' in 1923.
phenomenonA[comment] Garrod helped prove with even more evidence that DNA is the genetic information of organisms. By altering the genetic makeup of organisms, we can see that the proteins made are altered.
phenomenonB The genetic basis of sickle cell anemia demonstrates that the one-gene-one enzyme hypothesis is not quite correct.
phenomenonB[comment] We learned that sickle cell anemia is a Mendelian trait and is inherited as either heterozygous or homozygous. What I've learned that is profoundly important is that in heterozygous individuals, both genes may be expressed, but the dominant (favorable) trait expresses enough to result in normal function.

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] In Garrod's study of alkaptonuria, he found that out of his test subjects, those that were consanguineous were more likely to have the trait. This increased likelihood of heritability concluded that genes code for the enzymatic processes of the cell.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Beadle mutated Neurospora and found that by altering the genes in cells, he could alter the function of the enzymatic processes of the cell. Knowing that the genes code for the synthesis of these enzymes, he was able to isolate particular organisms to a single mutated gene. When a mutated organism is grown in a minimal media with its complementary supplement needed to grow (lacking the supplement results in non growth), he deduced that one gene codes for one enzyme.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Sickle cell anemia is a result of the Beta hemoglobin structure being altered as a result of a mutation. The hemoglobin structure is actually a result of complementary polypeptide chains. Vernon Ingram deduced through techniques that the alteration of a single polypeptide chain would result in sickle cell anemia.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Mutation is random and spontaneous, and through many generation, ideal mutations may manifest to alter an organism in a favorable manor. Genes will not mutate by influence but by random chance an organism may become selected for a favorable trait.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] In 1923, Gerard proposed a theory that certain diseases were due to hereditary errors in pathways that control chemical reactions in the body. While the terms “genes” and “enzymes” were not yet in use, the idea was the same: Gerard believed that certain diseases were due to defects in a pathway that would convert various substances into other products necessary for normal function.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The work of Gerard was the basis for the Beadle’s proposal of the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis. The hypothesis is based on the concept that genes are able to act through enzymes and that each gene codes for the translation of one enzyme. The enzyme produced is then used in a step of a metabolic pathway.
explainConcepts[SQ003] While the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis is very nearly accurate, it is not completely correct. Through studies of sickle cell anemia, it was able to be concluded that there were 2 main errors with the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis. First, while all enzymes are proteins not all proteins are enzymes. Second, proteins often consist of many polypeptides, and each polypeptide is coded for by a different gene. This led to the establishment of the more accurate one gene-one polypeptide hypothesis.
phenomenonA Archibald Gerard first suggested that genes controlled 'inborn errors of metabolism' in 1923.
phenomenonA[comment] This concept is fascinating to me as it directly relates to many genetic disorders and diseases. For example, both PKU and albinism result from an "inborn error in metabolism" when a certain metabolic pathway lacks an enzyme to convert one amino acid to another.
phenomenonB The genetic basis of sickle cell anemia demonstrates that the one-gene-one enzyme hypothesis is not quite correct.
phenomenonB[comment] One gene does not code for one protein, but many genes are critical in coding for the correct protein. Proteins have many different functions in our bodies...from histone proteins in our DNA to transport proteins found in our cell membranes. There are many diverse roles of proteins due to the differences in structure/folding of the many polypeptides.

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that Archibald Garrod was a practicing physician and from his investigations found that alkaptonuria is a metabolic pathway disorder that a person affected with this can not metabolize the alkapton 2,5-dihydroxyphenylacetic acid. This is excreted during urination, but if affected by this disorder urine is black.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] The one gene-one enzyme hypothesis is the idea that genes act through the production of enzymes, with each gene responsible for producing a single enzyme that in turn affects a single step in a metabolic pathway.In the mid-1930s they found that genes affecting eye color appeared to be serially dependent, and that the normal red eyes of Drosophila were the result of pigments that went through a series of transformations; different eye color gene mutations disrupted the transformations at a different points in the series. Thus, Beadle reasoned that each gene was responsible for an enzyme acting in the metabolic pathway of pigment synthesis. After these findings Beadle joined with Edward Tatum to investigate nutritional mutations in the pink bread mold Neurospora crassa.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] One-gene-one enzyme hypothesis changed to one-gene:one-polypeptide chain hypothesis. The need for these modifications of the original hypothesis became apparent during the analysis of hemoglobin structure in individuals afflicted with sickle-cell anemia. Affected individuals have erythrocytes that, under low oxygen tension, become elongated and curved because of the polymerization of hemoglobin. Sickle-Cell hemoglobin could be limited to differences in just a single polypeptide chain in a multimeric protein, leading to a "one gene-one polypeptide" hypothesis instead.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Mutations can be beneficial, neutral, or harmful for the organism, but mutations do not "try" to supply what the organism "needs." In this respect, mutations are random — whether a particular mutation happens or not is unrelated to how useful that mutation would be.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Before Archibald Gerard looked into inherited metabolic disorders, diseases were not looked at as something that is genetic in nature, but was always assumed to be the effect of viruses/parasites. However, after looking into some specific situations, Gerard suggested that genes controlled inborn errors of metabolism by analyzing how certain reactions in a pathway can cause diseases if blocked.
explainConcepts[SQ002] George Beadle and Edward Tatum proposed this one gene-one enzyme hypothesis studying the bread mold Neurospora crassa. They grew the mold on complete medium and if it would not grow, they knew that it must have a nutritional mutation. They then by trial and error plated the mutated strain on different mediums with different supplements until the deficiency was targeted. Whatever this deficiency was the specific thing that the mold could not synthesize.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The one gene-one enzyme hypothesis changed to the one gene-one polypeptide chain hypothesis due to two factors. One because nearly all enzymes are proteins, and two because proteins have a subunit structure that are at least 2 polypeptide chains.
phenomenonA Archibald Gerard first suggested that genes controlled 'inborn errors of metabolism' in 1923.
phenomenonA[comment] Both Alkaptonuria and penylketonuria are due to mutations that create a metabolic block in certain biochemical pathways in the body.
phenomenonB The genetic basis of sickle cell anemia demonstrates that the one-gene-one enzyme hypothesis is not quite correct.
phenomenonB[comment] The reason that one gene-one enzyme hypothesis was found out to be incorrect is due to the fact that a chemical difference is present between normal and sickle cell hemoglobin differing only by a single peptide fragment.

explainConcepts[SQ001] Inborn errors in metabolism are rare genetic disorders in which the body cannot breakdown food into useful energy. This is due to the defects in the specific proteins or enzymes which metabolize food. These proteins are coded for by specific genes, thus genes control the inborn errors of metabolism.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The one gene-one enzyme hypothesis is a theory which explains that one gene produces one enzyme that affects a step in the metabolic pathway. Beadle proposed this hypothesis by demonstrating that one gene in a fruit fly controlled one metabolic reaction which was also controlled by a specific enzyme.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The genetic basis of sickle cell anemia demonstrates that the one-gene-one enzyme hypothesis is not quite correct because the difference in the protein that causes sickle cell anemia is in the polypeptide. It shows that one gene can code for one polypeptide. All enzymes are proteins, but not all protein are polypeptides.

knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that mutations are random to an organism's needs because they are completely random. knowlegeBasis[SQ002] George Beadle was famous for working with Bread Mold (Neurospora Crassa) to come up with this revolutionizing statement in relation to the genetic code. This statement was the initial Cnetral Dogma, but was revised later on to be more specific once Sickle Cell disease was being studied.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that the one gene- one enzyme hypothesis was later revised to a more concise version of one gene-one polypeptide. This revision in the hypothesis was caused during the study of sickle cell anemia which is composed of two alpha subunits, two beta subunits( mutant), and heme groups--hence a quaternary protein structure. In sickle cell anemia, a mutation occurs in the beta chain thus causing it's sickle shaped and other symptoms. Since the mutation was within one polypeptide that was produced by an error in one area of the gene sequence, the new hypothesis was created.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Mutations occur at random rather than being influenced by some sort of selection pressure. A test was conducted by two scientists to determine where mutations are adaptive or random. In this experiment, it was hypothesized that if the E. Coli obtained mutations at their "will" when mixed with bacteriophages, the colony growth of e. Coli would be evenly distributed amongst all the bacterial progeny. However, if mutations were random, then mutations would be seen prior to the introduction of the bacteriophage as well as during infection. In addition, there should not be a constant growth in colonies amongst all bacterial progeny.

knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Beadle did experiments on Drosophila and Neurospora. This was the first evidence that mutations in genes would affect polypeptide chains (proteins); thus, led to the support of the one gene-one protein hypothesis. This research also produced the concept of molecular disease.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Mutations are not controlled or signal by cells or signal cascades. In other terms, mutations cannot be induced to adapt to any sort of change. Rather, mutations occur randomly regardless of the cell's needs. Then, those mutated or nonmutated cells with the best fitness will outlive the selective pressures or "needs" to live to pass on their genes.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Upon noting that multiple inherited diseases displayed harmful alterations in body chemistry, Archibald Gerard suggested that inherited disease was caused by an "inborn error of metabolism," thus first suggesting how genes work. Gerard studied families with alkaptonuria (causes black urine as a result of homogentisic acid in the urine) of whom affected members were more common as a result of first cousin marriages than unrelated marriages. He reasoned that healthy people metabolize homogentisic acid, but people afflicted with alkaptonuria lack the necessary enzyme and thus cannot metabolize HA.
explainConcepts[SQ002] George Beadle's experimented with nutritional mutations in bread mold and showed that genes are directly responsible for the synthesis of enzymes. He added radiation to conidia, then monitored its growth in the presence of amino supplements. Because mutant cells only grew when tyrosine was added, he determined that the mutation affected the synthesis of tyrosine.
explainConcepts[SQ003] While nearly all enzymes are proteins, not all proteins are enzymes. This, in addition to the fact that proteins have subunit structures consisting of two or more polypeptide chains, revamped the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis into the one gene-one polypeptide hypothesis. In regards to sickle cell anemia, chemical differences exist between normal and sickle-cell hemoglobin, and fingerprinting showed that these hemoglobins differed by a single peptide fragment.
phenomenonA The genetic basis of sickle cell anemia demonstrates that the one-gene-one enzyme hypothesis is not quite correct.
phenomenonA[comment] Two facts challenged the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis. In addition to the genetic basis of sickle cell anemia was the fact that while nearly all enzymes are proteins, not all proteins are enzymes.
phenomenonB George Beadle proposed the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis.
phenomenonB[comment] The one gene-one enzyme hypothesis was actually proposed by both George Beadle and Henry Tatum, who worked together on the conidia experiment.

I understand this led him to reason that healthy people metabolize homogentisic acid, but people afflicted with alkaptonuria lack the necessary enzyme and thus cannot metabolize HA.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that George Beadle's experiments with nutritional mutations in bread mold showed that genes are directly responsible for the synthesis of enzymes. explainConcepts[SQ001] Since genes code for all proteins found in the body, metabolism errors arise due to defects in genes. Metabolism is normally controlled by proteins and if the genes are defective the proteins will be non functional and there will be errors in metabolism
explainConcepts[SQ002] He observed yeast cells and upon mutation of a gene he saw that the protein corresponding to that gene was defective. he thus concluded that each gene coded for a protein.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Only one mutation on a gene causes the diseases. However, the protein is made up of several polypeptides and there are no mutations in other proteins. Thus the correct hypothesis is one gene one polypeptide and not protein. protein are made up of many polypeptides.
phenomenonA Archibald Gerard first suggested that genes controlled 'inborn errors of metabolism' in 1923.

phenomenonB George Beadle proposed the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis.
phenomenonB[comment] a gene normally codes for a polypeptide. protein is composed of multiple polypeptide which each gene codes for. Thus his hypothesis is wrong. an excellent example is sickle cell anemia which is caused due to a mutation in a single gene and a single polypeptide.

Many proteins/enzymes are made up of more than one polypeptide so the first hypothesis could not work. In studying sickle cell anemia, 2 different molecules of hemoglobin were discovered and only differed by one peptide fragment. This one fragment made the different between normal RBC or sickle cell.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Gerard was an English doctor who noticed that patients with metabolic deficiencies had disorders (PKU, alkaptonuria, etc) characterized by a lack of something, and these conditions were genetic, hence the "inborn".
explainConcepts[SQ002] Beadle did experiments with Neurospora that showed mutants only grew when whatever they were deficient in was provided them in the medium. Since Neurospora has a fairly linear biochemical pathway to produce arginine, the examination of mutants in the pathway led Beadle to propose that one gene made one enzyme product.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Sickle cell anemia is caused by a defective hemoglobin protein, which is defective because of a missense mutation caused by an incorrect amino acid in the peptide chain. This disproved the one-gene-one-enzyme hypothesis because there was not a lack of enzyme produced, but an issue with a polypeptide chain. Therefore the theory was modified to say one gene codes for one polypeptide.
phenomenonA George Beadle proposed the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis.
phenomenonA[comment] This was the basis for eventually understanding the role of proteins and understanding that most genes code for polypeptides, which is a very important concept to understand in molecular genetics which leads to understanding protein molecules and how molecules are deformed or why.
phenomenonB Archibald Gerard first suggested that genes controlled 'inborn errors of metabolism' in 1923.
phenomenonB[comment] Metabolic pathways like the one Gerard investigated can be very complex, as an example, glycolysis and human metabolism is extremely complex, requiring hundreds of steps and enzymes.

knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Mutations do not occur because an organism is deficient in something, mutations are always random and spontaneous. Therefore if a mutant has a need, that does not affect what mutation occurs. Also, some genes are naturally more likely to be susceptible to mutation than others, which also affects where genes occur. This means the mutation does not always happen where an organism needs it.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Archibald Gerard is the individual who discovered that genes control inborn errors of metabolism through his studies of alkaptonuria. Alkaptonuria is a disorder that makes an individuals urine to turn black. He figured out that this disorder along with others seem to be inherited. The cause of alkaptonuria is a malfunctioning enzyme that cannot metablolize the alkapton 2,5-dihydroxyphenylacetic acid, homogentisic acid. When Homogentisic acid accumulates in the body, it is oxidized to produce a black product that is excreted in the urine. Gerard referred to this malfunctioning enzyme, which is controlled by genes, as an "inborn error of metabolism."
explainConcepts[SQ002] The one gene-one enzyme hypothesis proposed by George Beadle was the first to provide a convincing experimental evidence proving genes are directly responsible for the synthesis of enzymes. Beadle conducted two experiements the first involving Drosophila and the second invovling Neurospora crassa which lead to his one-gen one enzyme hypothesis. In the drosophila study he figured out that the mutant genes that cause different color eyes could be linked to malfunctioning enzymes. The Neurospora crassa study looked at a nutritional mutation which was caused by the inability for the organism to carry out an important chemical conversion reaction. Together these lead to the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis, which was later proven false.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Sickle cell anemia, a disorder characterized by mutant hemoglobin. In individuals with sickle cell anemia when oxygen levels are low, hemoglobin become elongated and aggregate together depriving tissues of oxygen. The study of this diseases helped disprove the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis. These investigations proved that a single gene codes for a single polypeptide chain and that a mutation can affect an individual's phenotype by causing a single amino acid substitution.
phenomenonA The genetic basis of sickle cell anemia demonstrates that the one-gene-one enzyme hypothesis is not quite correct.
phenomenonA[comment] Sickle cell anemia is a life threatening disease that affects about 1 in every 625 African-American infants and currently affects 50,000 to 75,000 individuals. Understanding the genetic basis for this disease is important for its treatment. Also, knowing that one gene codes for one polypeptide instead of one enzyme is important because it helps determine the cause of many other disorders.
phenomenonB Archibald Gerard first suggested that genes controlled 'inborn errors of metabolism' in 1923.
phenomenonB[comment] Archibald Gerard's finding that genes are control of "inborn errors of metabolism" that cause disorders was important because it helped determine the cause of a variety of human disorders. This finding lead to many other studies which have since been able to prove that gene mutations can cause multiple disorders caused by metabolism errors.

groupTime460 199.1

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Garrod's hypothesis stems from an investigation into families exhibiting a disease known as alkaptonuria, which is an organic acid metabolism abnormality that causes urine to darken from yellow to brown once exposed to air. Later in their life, individuals with the disease develop arthritis with brown pigmentation in the effected joint cartilage/connective tissue. Garrod followed the inheritance of the disease, observing that it followed an autosomal recessive pattern, and postulated that it was caused by a mutation in a gene encoding an enzyme involved in the metabolism of a class of compounds called alkapton. Over the next decade he developed an understanding of the possible nature of inherited diseases of metabolism, specializing in the nature of recessive inheritance of enzyme defects. Garrod expanded his metabolic studies to cover cystinuria, pentosuria, and albinism, and in 1923 he summarized these studies in an expanded edition of his best known work.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Beadle and Tatum's key experiments involved exposing the bread mold Neurospora crassa to x-rays, causing mutations. In a series of experiments, they showed that these mutations caused changes in specific enzymes involved in metabolic pathways. The one gene-one enzyme hypothesis is the idea that genes act through the production of enzymes, with each gene responsible for producing a single enzyme that in turn affects a single step in a metabolic pathway.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The one gene-one enzyme hypothesis was further modified in 1962 by Vernon Ingram, and from it, the one gene-one polypeptide hypothesis was born. In 1949, it was proposed that sickling was caused by a single gene mutation, which was heterozygous in sickle cell trait individuals and homozygous in individuals with full sickle cell anemia. Simultaneously, it was also noted that the hemoglobin from normal individuals and that from sickle cell anemic individuals migrated differently on an electrophoresis plate, illustrating that there was a physical difference in the hemoglobin types and supporting the single gene mutation. Ingram analyzed the different polypeptide chains in hemoglobin molecules using a modified form of Frederick Sanger's protein analysis. This technique gave a fingerprint of the different hemoglobin types; this showed that the differences between the two types of hemoglobin could be found in one peptide section of eight amino acids. When this section was isolated and analyzed, the only difference was one amino acid (glutamic acid in normal and valine in sickle cell hemoglobin). The difference between these amino acids was one base in the triplet codon. Further analysis showed that amino acid changes in one chain were independent of changes in the other chain, suggesting that the genes determining the alpha and beta chains were located at different loci and show independent assortment. From this, it can be seen that hemoglobin is composed of two independent gene products, each of which is a separate polypeptide. The gene is a section of DNA that determines the amino acid sequence of a polypeptide. One gene codes for one polypeptide and several polypeptides may be required for a functional protein or enzyme.
phenomenonA Archibald Gerard first suggested that genes controlled 'inborn errors of metabolism' in 1923.
phenomenonA[comment] Garrod was the first to identify the relationship between diseases, their inheritance pattern, and the structure of DNA/genetic material. This was the foundation for so much work now being done by geneticists, biologists, chemists, and pathologists studying how to prevent and treat genetic diseases/conditions.
phenomenonB George Beadle proposed the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis.
phenomenonB[comment] I thought it was awesome how Beadle and Tatum used their experiments to systematically determine the elements of biochemical processes and eventually determine the mis-transcription of only one base could cause the mis-translation and production of an amino acid leading to an entirely different, and faulty protein product.

explainConcepts[SQ002] The one gene–one enzyme hypothesis, proposed by George Wells Beadle in 1941, is the theory that each gene directly produces a single enzyme, which consequently affects an individual step in a metabolic pathway. In 1941, Beadle demonstrated that one gene in a fruit fly controlled a single, specific chemical reaction in the fruit fly, which one enzyme controlled.
explainConcepts[SQ003] By the early 1950s, advances in biochemical genetics spurred by the original hypothesis, made the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis seem very unlikely. groupTime460 24.29

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Gerard's study of inborn errors of metabolism helped to establish that proteins did play a role in heredity. He noticed that some inherited diseases caused harmful alterations in body chemistry. He studied families with alkaptonuria and reasoned that they lacked the proper enzyme to metabolize homogentisic acid. He established that it was a genetic trait because families had several affected members.
explainConcepts[SQ002] George Beadle studied Neurospora to establish that genes are directly responsible for the synthesis of enzymes. He showed that nutritional mutations in bread mold caused the loss of enzymatic activity. Beadle targeted the metabolic pathway in Neurospora that synthesized arginine. He studied 7 auxotroph mutant strains that were unable to convert citrulline to arginine.
explainConcepts[SQ003] We now know that the one-gene-one-enzyme should really be one-gene-one polypeptide because proteins are made up of more than one polypeptide. A sickle cell and a normal cell only differ by one peptide fragment, yet they have many chemical differences.
phenomenonA Archibald Gerard first suggested that genes controlled 'inborn errors of metabolism' in 1923.
phenomenonA[comment] Since Gerard's studies, many different different diseases of metabolism have been discovered. One is PKU, in which individuals lack the enzyme phenylalanine hydroxylase and therefore can not convert phenylalanine to tyrosine. This causes a build up of phenylalanine in the cerebrospinal fluid leading to mental retardation.
phenomenonB The genetic basis of sickle cell anemia demonstrates that the one-gene-one enzyme hypothesis is not quite correct.
phenomenonB[comment] There are many different mutations that can cause the hemoglobin cell to become sickling. However, it seems that only mutations in the beta polypeptide chain, not the alpha, can cause the disease. Most specifically, the substitution of Glu for Val on 6th position of the beta chain causes the most common form of sickle cell anemia.

I understand that since his work, many more metabolic diseases have been discovered that can be tied to a genetic basis.

I understand that his hypothesis was not entirely correct, but led to a better understanding of the relationship between genes and proteins.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that nearly all enzymes are proteins, but not all proteins are enzymes. I understand that proteins have a subunit structure with two or more polypeptide chains. knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that mutations occur randomly or are induced. Spontaneous mutations occur naturally and arise from biological or chemical processes that alter the nitrogenous bases. Mutations are not directed and do not arise from environmental changes.

groupTime460 7.59

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Archibald Garrod discovered inborn errors of metabolism. An explanation for epistasis is an important manifestation of Garrod’s research, albeit indirectly. When Garrod studied alkaptonuria, a disorder that makes urine quickly turn black due to the presence of gentesate, he noticed that it was prevalent among populations whose parents were closely related
explainConcepts[SQ002] The one gene-one enzyme hypothesis is the idea that genes act through the production of enzymes, with each gene responsible for producing a single enzyme that in turn affects a single step in a metabolic pathway. The concept was proposed by George Beadle and Edward Tatum in an influential 1941 paper on genetic mutations in the mold Neurospora crassa, and subsequently was dubbed the "one gene-one enzyme hypothesis" by their collaborator Norman Horowitz. In 2004 Norman Horowitz reminisced that “these experiments founded the science of what Beadle and Tatum called ‘biochemical genetics.’ In actuality they proved to be the opening gun in what became molecular genetics and all the developments that have followed from that.” The development of the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis is often considered the first significant result in what came to be called molecular biology. Although it has been extremely influential, the hypothesis was recognized soon after its proposal to be an oversimplification. Even the subsequent reformulation of the "one gene-one polypeptide" hypothesis is now considered too simple to describe the relationship between genes and proteins.
explainConcepts[SQ003] By the early 1950s, advances in biochemical genetics—spurred in part by the original hypothesis—made the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis seem very unlikely (at least in its original form). Beginning in 1957, Vernon Ingram and others showed through protein fingerprinting that genetic variations in proteins (such as sickle cell hemoglobin) could be limited to differences in just a single polypeptide chain in a multimeric protein, leading to a "one gene-one polypeptide" hypothesis instead.According to geneticist Rowland H. Davis, "By 1958 – indeed, even by 1948 – one gene, one enzyme was no longer a hypothesis to be resolutely defended; it was simply the name of a research program."
phenomenonA Archibald Gerard first suggested that genes controlled 'inborn errors of metabolism' in 1923.
phenomenonA[comment] Archibald Garrod discovered inborn errors of metabolism. An explanation for epistasis is an important manifestation of Garrod’s research, albeit indirectly. When Garrod studied alkaptonuria, a disorder that makes urine quickly turn black due to the presence of gentesate, he noticed that it was prevalent among populations whose parents were closely related
phenomenonB The genetic basis of sickle cell anemia demonstrates that the one-gene-one enzyme hypothesis is not quite correct.

Davis, "By 1958 – indeed, even by 1948 – one gene, one enzyme was no longer a hypothesis to be resolutely defended; it was simply the name of a research program."
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Mutations can be beneficial, neutral, or harmful for the organism, but mutations do not "try" to supply what the organism "needs." Factors in the environment may influence the rate of mutation but are not generally thought to influence the direction of mutation. For example, exposure to harmful chemicals may increase the mutation rate, but will not cause more mutations that make the organism resistant to those chemicals. In this respect, mutations are random — whether a particular mutation happens or not is unrelated to how useful that mutation would be.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] While studying a disease, Archibald Gerald was able to find a link to epistasis, which was an important point to conclude that genes were responsible for the regulation of "inborn errors of metabolism.'
explainConcepts[SQ002] Through George Beadle's experimentation, he concluded that one specific gene was responsible for the coding of one specific enzyme.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Sickle cell anemia is an example which disproves Beadle's one-gene enzyme hypothesis.
phenomenonA George Beadle proposed the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis.
phenomenonA[comment] We know now that many genes can code for various proteins, which suggest some type of regulating mechanism for genes. Understanding this underlying mechanism will allow scientists to broaden the scope of the genetic field.
phenomenonB The genetic basis of sickle cell anemia demonstrates that the one-gene-one enzyme hypothesis is not quite correct.
phenomenonB[comment] For some time, the one-gene-one-enzyme hypothesis was prevalent. The discovery and better understanding of sickle cell anemia allows scientists to disprove the traditional hypothesis and develop a new one according to new data and information.

This is dangerous because it induces a higher risk of blood clotting and strokes. With the better understanding of this disease came a better understanding that the one-gene-one-enzyme hypothesis was incorrect.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Mutations are random but they happen in according to an organism's needs. In this case, these mutations are referred to as conferring a selective advantage.
